{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521699","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521699"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:36:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:36:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13712"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13712","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13712"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.02,0.62,0.11,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6331"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67682"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6331"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13712"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53139"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"17"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"278"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5768"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14553"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30621"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67682","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67682"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic requesting a prescription for modafinil. He works as a long-haul truck driver and reports struggling with daytime sleepiness during overnight shifts. He denies any near misses or accidents but admits to having difficulty staying awake while driving. He requests that this information be kept confidential as disclosure could jeopardise his employment. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His body mass index is 32 kg/m2.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Report to the driver licensing authority","Prescribe modafinil with regular review","Advise to cease driving until medically assessed","Maintain strict confidentiality and refer for sleep study","Document concerns but take no immediate action"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents an ethical dilemma between patient confidentiality and public safety. The patient\u0027s symptoms suggest possible obstructive sleep apnoea, which poses a significant risk to road safety given his occupation as a commercial driver.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdvising to cease driving until medically assessed\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first step. Doctors have both an ethical and legal duty to advise patients who are medically unfit to drive to stop driving. This is particularly important for commercial drivers given their increased time on road and potential for causing serious harm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReporting to the driver licensing authority\u003C/strong\u003E may eventually be necessary but is not the first step. In Australia, only South Australia and Northern Territory mandate reporting of medically unfit drivers. Other jurisdictions allow discretionary reporting with legal protection for the reporting doctor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrescribing modafinil with regular review\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as it enables potentially dangerous behaviour without addressing the underlying medical condition. It may also constitute off-label prescribing given the absence of a formal diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaintaining strict confidentiality and referring for sleep study\u003C/strong\u003E fails to address the immediate safety risk. While investigation is important, the priority is to prevent harm to the patient and public.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDocumenting concerns but taking no immediate action\u003C/strong\u003E would be negligent given the clear risk to public safety. Doctors have a duty of care that extends beyond just the individual patient in such situations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Doctors have an ethical and legal duty to advise patients who are unfit to drive to cease driving.","Mandatory reporting of medically unfit drivers varies by state/territory in Australia.","Patient confidentiality may be breached to prevent serious harm to others."],"references":["Assessing Fitness to Drive 2022 [Internet]. Austroads; 2017. Available at: https://austroads.com.au/publications/assessing-fitness-to-drive/ap-g56/legislation-relating-to-reporting"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53139"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13712"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53139"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-06T15:03:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-06T15:03:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6331"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67682"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"17","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/17"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude07","name":"Bioethics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"it